<section class="mt-8">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">How to Use This Calculator</h2>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Here is exactly how to use this percent decrease calculator in three steps.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Step 1 — Enter the original value</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">This is your starting point — the original value before any percentage decrease. The price before the discount. Your old salary. Last month's bills. Type it into the first box.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Step 2 — Enter the new value</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">This is the number after the drop. The sale price. Your new salary. This month's lower expenses. Type it into the second box.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Step 3 — Click calculate</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">That is all. The tool will calculate the percentage drop instantly.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">What you will see</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">A clear percentage decrease. Something like "25% decrease." Plus the exact difference between the two numbers, shown as a negative like "−50".</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">What if you mix up the order?</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The calculator checks for that. If you put the smaller number first and the larger number second, it will notice and point you to the <a href="/tools/percent-increase/" class="text-[#1D9E75] hover:text-[#168561] underline font-medium">Percent Increase Calculator</a>. That tool handles growth.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Reverse calculation</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Here is something handy — this tool also supports reverse percentage decrease calculation. If you know the original number and the percentage you want to take off, you can work backwards. For example, "decrease 100 by 20% and get 80." I will show you the formula in a bit.</p>
</section>

<section class="mt-8">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">What Does Percentage Decrease Actually Measure?</h2>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Here is the simple version of what percentage decrease means. Percentage decrease tells you how much something shrank, compared to where it started. One question: "How big was the relative percentage drop compared to the original?"</p>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Let me show you why that question matters.</p>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">A business loses $10,000. Sounds bad. But without knowing the starting point, you have no idea how bad. If the business started with $20,000, losing $10,000 means it lost half of everything. That is a 50% decrease. If the business started with $10,000,000, losing $10,000 is only a 0.1% decrease. That is nothing.</p>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Same loss. Completely different story. This is why percentage decrease matters in real life. Percentage decrease tells you which story you are in.</p>
</section>


<section class="mt-8">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">Breaking Down the Percent Decrease Formula</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">The Formula</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Here is the percent decrease formula. It looks like the increase formula, but there is one important difference.</p>

  <div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-6">
    ((Original Value − New Value) / Original Value) × 100
  </div>

  <img
    src="/images/percent-decrease.webp"
    alt="Percent decrease formula: ((Original Value minus New Value) divided by Original Value) times 100"
    class="w-full rounded-lg border border-slate-200 my-6"
    loading="lazy"
    width="1200"
    height="400"
  />

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Here is how to calculate percentage decrease step by step. Notice the subtraction — increase uses new minus original. Decrease uses original minus new. That is on purpose.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Why the Subtraction Order Matters</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">When something goes down, the original number is bigger than the new number. So original minus new gives you a positive number. That is the amount of the decrease. Exactly what you want.</p>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">If you accidentally do new minus original, you get a negative number. Then you divide. Then you multiply. You end up with a negative percentage. That is mathematically correct — a negative does tell you there was a decrease. But it looks wrong. Most people expect a positive number when talking about a drop. So the formula flips the subtraction to keep things clean. Getting this wrong is the most common mistake I see. <span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Always do original minus new for percentage decrease.</span></p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Worked Formula Example</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Here is a percentage decrease formula example. A product costs $100. Then it goes on sale for $75.</p>

  <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6 shadow-sm">
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">(100 − 75) / 100 × 100 = 25 / 100 × 100 = <span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">25%</span></p>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">That is a 25% decrease. You saved a quarter of the original price.</p>
  </div>
</section>


<section class="mt-8">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">How to Decrease a Number by a Known Percentage</h2>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Here is how to decrease a number by a percentage when you already know the rate. Sometimes you have the original number and the percentage you want to take off. You need the new number. For example, "What is $80 after a 15% decrease?"</p>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Here is the formula:</p>

  <div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-6">
    New Value = Original Value × (1 − Percentage / 100)
  </div>

  <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6 shadow-sm">
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">For $80 with a 15% decrease: $80 decreased by 15% to <span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">$68</span>.</p>
  </div>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">You see this percentage decrease formula for discounts, pay cuts, and budget reductions all the time.</p>
</section>

<section class="mt-8">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">How to Work Backwards — Finding the Original Value</h2>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">This section is only on this page. People ask me this all the time — how to find the original price after a percentage decrease. "I know the sale price and the discount percentage. What was the original price?"</p>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Here is the reverse percentage decrease formula:</p>

  <div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-6">
    Original Value = New Value / (1 − Percentage / 100)
  </div>

  <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6 shadow-sm">
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4"><span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Retail example.</span> You buy a jacket on sale for $68. The tag says it was 15% off. Original price: $68 / (1 − 15 / 100) = $80. You saved $12.</p>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed"><span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Finance example.</span> You get a paycheck for $3,400 after taxes. Your tax rate is 15%. That means you earned $4,000 before taxes. You lost $600.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="mt-8">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">Percentage Decrease — 5 Worked Examples</h2>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Here are five percentage decrease examples from real life. Same formula each time.</p>

  <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6 shadow-sm">
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Example 1 — Retail discount</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">A laptop costs $120. It goes on sale for $84.</p>
    <div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-4">
      (120 − 84) / 120 × 100 = 36 / 120 × 100 = 30%
    </div>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">The laptop is 30% off.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6 shadow-sm">
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Example 2 — Salary reduction</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Use this to calculate percentage decrease in salary. You made $55,000. Then your pay drops to $49,500.</p>
    <div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-4">
      (55,000 − 49,500) / 55,000 × 100 = 5,500 / 55,000 × 100 = 10%
    </div>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Your salary decreased by 10%.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6 shadow-sm">
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Example 3 — Business operating costs</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Monthly costs were $18,000. You find a cheaper supplier. Costs drop to $14,400.</p>
    <div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-4">
      (18,000 − 14,400) / 18,000 × 100 = 3,600 / 18,000 × 100 = 20%
    </div>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Costs decreased by 20%.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6 shadow-sm">
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Example 4 — Investment portfolio loss</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Here is how to track percentage decrease in an investment portfolio. Your portfolio was $25,000. The market dips. It drops to $19,500.</p>
    <div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-4">
      (25,000 − 19,500) / 25,000 × 100 = 5,500 / 25,000 × 100 = 22%
    </div>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">You lost 22%.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6 shadow-sm">
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Example 5 — Weight loss</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">This formula also shows how to calculate weight loss percentage. You weigh 210 pounds. After a few months, you weigh 189 pounds.</p>
    <div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-4">
      (210 − 189) / 210 × 100 = 21 / 210 × 100 = 10%
    </div>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">You lost 10% of your body weight.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="mt-8">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">Where Percentage Decrease Is Used in Real Life</h2>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Here are the most common percentage decrease in real life examples.</p>

  <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6 shadow-sm">
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Retail discounts</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">You see "30% off." Do the math yourself. Original minus sale, divided by original, times 100. If the numbers do not match, the sign is wrong.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Tax and after-tax income</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">This is how you calculate percentage decrease in income after tax. You make $60,000. You take home $48,000.</p>
    <div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-4">
      (60,000 − 48,000) / 60,000 × 100 = 20%
    </div>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">You lose 20% to taxes.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Asset depreciation</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The same formula works as a car depreciation percentage calculator. You buy a car for $28,000. Five years later it is worth $16,800.</p>
    <div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-4">
      (28,000 − 16,800) / 28,000 × 100 = 40%
    </div>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Your car lost 40% of its value. <a href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/d/depreciation.asp" class="text-[#1D9E75] hover:text-[#168561] underline font-medium" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Learn more about depreciation</a>.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Energy reduction</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">You can also track percentage decrease in energy bills. Your electric bill was $200. You make some changes. It drops to $160.</p>
    <div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-4">
      (200 − 160) / 200 × 100 = 20%
    </div>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">You cut your usage by 20%.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Inflation impact</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4"><a href="https://www.imf.org/en/Research/inflation" class="text-[#1D9E75] hover:text-[#168561] underline font-medium" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Inflation</a> at 5% means your money buys about 5% less. Economists track GDP drops and unemployment rises using percentages. It is the only fair way to compare across different countries and time periods.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="mt-8">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">Percentage Decrease vs. Percentage Change vs. Percentage Points</h2>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">People confuse percentage decrease vs percentage change all the time. Let me clear it up.</p>

  <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6 shadow-sm">
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Percentage decrease</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Only for when numbers go down. Formula: ((Original − New) / Original) × 100. The answer is positive.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Percentage change</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Works for both up and down. Formula: ((New − Original) / Original) × 100. For a decrease, the answer is negative. For an increase, it is positive.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Percentage points</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Measure the raw gap between two percentages. Example: Interest rate drops from 5% to 4%. That is a 1 percentage point drop. But the percentage decrease is (5 − 4) / 5 × 100 = 20%. Both are correct. They answer different questions. That is the key difference between percentage points and percentage decrease.</p>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">If someone says "rates dropped by 1%," ask them: "One percentage point or one percent?" The difference matters for mortgages, loans, and investments.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="mt-8">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">Tracking Percentage Decrease Over Time</h2>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The same formula works when you need to track percentage decrease over time. You buy a car for $28,000. Five years later it is worth $16,800.</p>

  <div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-6">
    (28,000 − 16,800) / 28,000 × 100 = 40% total depreciation
  </div>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">You can track monthly declines too. Revenue drops from $50,000 to $45,000. That is a 10% monthly decrease. Catching these early helps you fix problems before they get worse.</p>

  <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6 shadow-sm">
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4"><span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">A serious warning.</span> Here is how to calculate total percentage decrease over multiple periods — do not average them. If revenue drops 10% in January and another 10% in February, the total decrease is not 20%. It is 19%. Why? Because the second 10% applies to a smaller number. Always use the start and end values to calculate total decline. Ignore the middle.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="mt-8">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">Common Mistakes When Calculating Percentage Decrease</h2>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Here are the most common percentage decrease mistakes and how to avoid them.</p>

  <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6 shadow-sm">
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Mistake 1 — Dividing by the new value instead of the original</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">From $100 to $75. This is the most common percentage decrease wrong formula error — always divide by the original.</p>
    <div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-4">
      <p class="mb-2">❌ Wrong: 25 / 75 = 33%</p>
      <p>✓ Right: 25 / 100 = 25%</p>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Mistake 2 — Reversing the subtraction order</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">For decrease, always do original minus new. New minus original gives you a negative. Avoid the confusion. Keep it positive.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Mistake 3 — Forgetting to multiply by 100</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">You subtract. You divide. You get 0.25. That is not a percentage — it is a percentage decrease decimal. Multiply by 100. Get 25%.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Mistake 4 — Confusing percentage decrease with percentage points</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">From 5% to 4% is a 1 percentage point drop. It is also a 20% percentage decrease. Know which one you are talking about.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Mistake 5 — Averaging percentage decreases across periods</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Use start and end values only. Do not average. It gives the wrong answer.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="mt-10 space-y-6">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">FAQ — Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <div>
    <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-2">What is the formula for percentage decrease?</p>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">((Original Value − New Value) / Original Value) × 100.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-2">How do I calculate the percentage decrease in Excel?</p>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Put original in A1, new in B1. Use <span class="font-mono bg-slate-100 px-1 rounded">=(A1−B1)/A1</span>. Then format the cell as a percentage.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-2">What is the difference between percentage decrease and percentage change?</p>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Percentage decrease only applies when numbers go down. Percentage change works for both, but the result is negative for decreases.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-2">How do I decrease a number by a specific percentage?</p>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">New Value = Original Value × (1 − Percentage / 100). Example: $100 decreased by 20% = $80.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-2">What is the difference between percentage decrease and percentage points?</p>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Percentage decrease measures relative shrinkage. Percentage points measure the raw gap. A drop from 5% to 4% is a 1 percentage point drop but a 20% percentage decrease.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-2">How do I find the original value before a percentage decrease?</p>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Original Value = New Value / (1 − Percentage / 100). Example: You paid $68 after a 15% discount. Original price was $80.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-2">Can percentage decrease exceed 100%?</p>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Yes. From 100 to 0 is 100%. From 100 to −50 is 150%. But for most everyday situations — prices, salaries, weights — it stays between 0% and 100%.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-2">How do I track percentage decrease over multiple periods?</p>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Use the start and end values only. Do not average percentages. The middle periods do not matter for the total.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="mt-8">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">Conclusion</h2>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Let me bring it back to where we started. That "30% off" sign. That pay cut sounded small. Those investment losses. Raw numbers hide the truth. Percentage decrease reveals it. It tells you not just how much fell, but how much of the original you lost. The formula is simple: original minus new, divided by original, times 100. The calculator at the top does the work for you. Enter two numbers. Click calculate. Get your answer instantly.</p>
